At the end of February, Vietnam, China's neighbor, was particularly quiet, with 22 consecutive days without new cases, even as the number of confirmed cases increased in a number of countries around the world. As life gradually returned to normal, a plane from London, England, to Hanoi, the capital of Vietnam, broke the silence.

On March 6, Vietnam reported the 17th confirmed case of new pneumonia, the first new diagnosis since the 16th since 25 February in Foshan, Vietnam, which was also the last case to be cured and discharged from hospital, ending a 10-day "zero case" state. March 6th is Friday. Vietnam's stock market resumed trading on Monday, down more than 6 percent.

Mr. Liu, a resident of Vietnam, told interface news that on the second day after the 17th case was reported, supermarkets were buying up the food he had ordered online and had not delivered it, "only received a letter of apology for being out of stock. ".

The 17th case means Vietnam is entering the second phase of prevention and control of the epidemic, which will be more difficult than before as the epidemic has spread to more than 100 countries around the world, Deputy Prime Minister Vu Teh Chan said.

The 17th case is a 26-year-old female Vietnamese tourist returning from the UK who arrived at Hanoi Pai Airport on 2 March in Business Class on VN0054 of Air Vietnam before returning to her home in Hanoi. On 5 March, she was admitted to hospital with a high fever, cough and weakness. She was subsequently diagnosed with new crown pneumonia.

The patient, who flew from Hanoi to London on February 15, travelled to the heavily affected cities of Milan, Italy, on February 18 and Paris, France, on February 25. He developed cough and weakness on February 29, but had no fever at the time. The patient boarded a flight back to Vietnam without seeking medical attention and concealed a medical condition upon arrival. She has been transferred to a negative pressure isolation ward at the Central Tropical Diseases Hospital, Đông Anh.

In the following two days, 13 new cases of coronavirus were confirmed in Viet Nam, 10 of whom were passengers of flight VN0054, aged 58 to 74, nine of whom were travelling in business class and one in economy class; Two other Vietnamese were close contacts of the 17th case.

VN0054 had a total of 217 passengers, including 21 business class passengers and 180 economy class passengers, as well as 16 crew members, Vietnam Express reported. Vietnam's Minister of Planning and Investment, Nguyen Chi Dung, was on the same flight, but he tested negative for the new coronavirus on both occasions.

As of 11:30 am on March 9, the cumulative number of confirmed cases in Vietnam has surged to 30, distributed in 10 provinces and cities across the country, with 100 suspected cases and no deaths yet. All newly confirmed cases are in stable condition. In terms of nationality, seven Britons, five Vietnamese, one Irishman and one Mexican were recently added.

According to the movement track in Vietnam of four imported cases reported by Quảng Ninh, the confirmed cases travelled to Ha Long Bay and other tourist areas by train, bus and plane upon arrival. The province has sealed off two hotels where the confirmed patients had lived and quarantined 127 close contacts. The 18 cruise ships on which the 17th case travelled, the villages of close contacts and the areas of stay were also temporarily closed.

After the 17th case was confirmed, the Hanoi government also promptly took preventive and control measures, starting from the evening of the 6th, blockading a 500-meter-long section of the street where the case was located, in which 22 families of about 176 people were all required to stay in isolation for 14 days, some people living next door to the confirmed cases were sent to the Central Tropical Disease Hospital in Đông Anh for isolation. Lao Kai province, where two confirmed patients visited, has also quarantined 180 close contacts.

Currently, the Vietnamese government has contacted the VN0054 flight 176 passengers, only 60 people in Hanoi, others scattered around. Vietnam is also actively looking for other passengers, as well as those who have close contact with the confirmed patients.

In addition to breaking the "zero case" of the 17th patient, followed by the 18th case is a long-lived South Korean Vietnamese, 4 returned from Daegu, South Korea, was quarantined immediately after entry. French radio (RFI) said the outbreak in South Korea is also a potential threat to Vietnam. The two countries trade frequently, with nearly 48,000 Vietnamese working in South Korea, including 4,000 in Daegu and Gyeongbuk, the centers of the outbreak.

Wu Dezhan pointed out that in fact the new crown pneumonia epidemic has been "hidden ambush" in Vietnam, if not effectively controlled, there will be domestic and foreign trouble situation. He said Vietnam had developed plans to deal with a variety of situations, including thousands of confirmed cases in the country, and dozens or even hundreds of new cases could be added in the coming days.

From March 7, all visitors to Vietnam, regardless of their Vietnamese nationality, will be required to complete an electronic health declaration, and anyone who has travelled to or through China, South Korea, Iran and Italy will be placed in 14-day concentrated isolation. Starting from the morning of 10 March, Viet Nam will implement a nationwide health declaration system and all residents and tourists in Viet Nam will be required to complete the compulsory health declaration procedure.

The Vietnamese steering committee also recommended suspending visa-free access for the European Union and the United Kingdom, as well as other countries with cumulative confirmed cases of more than 500 or 50 new cases per day. Any foreign visitors with fever or other symptoms will be prohibited from entering the country.

On the morning of March 9,20 provinces and municipalities in Viet Nam extended the suspension dates of primary and secondary schools again, including Hanoi and Ho Chi Minh City, to March 15. Under the original plan, high schools in many districts of Viet Nam resumed classes on 2 March, while Lower Secondary, primary and pre-primary education schools continued to suspend classes for another week to 15 days.
